  <div id=PPTC2 class=CTxt style='display:none'><font size=2>
  <ul>
   <li>Gate-level minimization refers to the design task of finding an optimal
       gate-level implementation of Boolean functions describing a digital
       circuit.</li>
  </ul>
  </font></div>
  </td>
 </tr>
 <tr onmouseover="Over(this)" onmouseout="Out(this)" onclick="Follow(this)"
  style='cursor:hand'>
  <td align=right valign=top>
  <div class=sldNum><font size=2>3</font></div>
  </td>
  <td>
  <div id=PPTP3 class=PTxt><font size=2><a
  href="javascript:GoToSld('slide0003.htm');" id=PPTL3>3-2	The Map Method</a></font></div>
  <div id=PPTC3 class=CTxt style='display:none'><font size=2>
  <ul>
   <li>The complexity of the digital logic gates</li>
   <ul>
    <li>The complexity of the algebraic expression</li>
   </ul>
   <li>Logic minimization</li>
   <ul>
    <li>Algebraic approaches: lack specific rules</li>
    <li>The Karnaugh map</li>
    <ul>
     <li>A simple straight forward procedure</li>
     <li>A pictorial form of a truth table</li>
     <li>Applicable if the # of variables &lt; 7</li>
    </ul>
   </ul>
   <li>A diagram made up of squares</li>
   <ul>
    <li>Each square represents one minterm</li>
   </ul>
  </ul>
  </font></div>
  </td>
 </tr>
 <tr onmouseover="Over(this)" onmouseout="Out(this)" onclick="Follow(this)"
  style='cursor:hand'>
